These weights are defined such that in the resulting pseudopopulation, within every covariate stratum \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\textbf{z}$$\end{document} there is an equal proportion with and without infection. Note that by construction, these weights are equal to 1 among the infected, and thus only the uninfected group is re-weighted. These weights have a connection to propensity score weighting, where weights are defined based on the inverse probability of receiving the assigned treatment conditional on covariates. In particular, by including in the numerator the probability of being infected these weights are analogous to propensity score weighting towards an Average Treatment Effect on the Treated [20]. However, there is a conceptual difference in that infection status is modeled as the outcome in Eq. (2) rather than the exposure. In this way the weights also resemble ‘class weights’ for classification of imbalanced binary data, which inversely weight the members of the smaller outcome group by their proportion to the larger outcome group, such that in the weighted pseudopopulation there are equal proportions of each outcome.

