Then, in an independent dataset from the same data generating mechanism, we computed the numeric LCRI in Eq. (3), and evaluated two metrics characterizing its ability to discriminate individuals truly with and without LC: 1) the area under the receiver operating characteristic curve and 2) the area under the precision-recall curve. In both cases, higher values indicate better discrimination. For comparison to the LCRI, we considered an ad hoc score defined as the total number of symptoms an individual has. This comparator conceptually corresponds to approaches such as Fineberg et al. [17] that include the presence of any symptoms when defining LC. It mathematically corresponds to the computation in Eq. (3) fixing \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
