This manuscript provides strong evidence in support of using Lasso-penalized logistic regression, with history of infection as a pseudo-label, to identify LC-associated features and define an associated research index. In the context of ‘negative-unlabeled’ outcome data where LC status lacks a gold standard definition, rigorous simulation studies are an important tool for understanding the characteristics of the LCRI methodology. These simulations indicated that performance of the regression-based Long COVID research index is robust to complex correlation structures between symptoms, and that balancing weights could effectively mitigate the impact of confounding bias on LCRI performance. Interestingly, the findings also showed that both a large imbalance in the stratifying variables by infection status, and a strong association between the stratifying variables and symptoms, were necessary to observe differences between weighted and unweighted analyses. Future work could also help explore other factors that may affect performance, such as sample size and dimensionality, or temporal changes in infection rate \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
